<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="249" pageId="1" pageNumber="248" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1963,2023]" box="[151,1437,1999,2023]" pageId="1" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis box="[151,309,1999,2023]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="248">Female aptera</emphasis>
. With the generic character states indicated. Body generally pale yellow, extreme apex of abdomen and
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,154,1042]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">
<materialsCitation collectionCode="VI, IV, V" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" specimenCount="3" typeStatus="paratype">
mouth cone pale brown. Antennal segment I pale yellow; II–III mainly yellow, IV–V slightly brown; 
<collectionCode box="[1250,1278,154,177]" country="Norway" name="Mykotektet, National Veterinary Institute" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">VI</collectionCode>
darker toward at apex (
<figureCitation box="[243,310,190,214]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–14" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1748,1770]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–14. Aptinothrips species.Female. Tergites III–V (1–3): (1) A. elegans, (2) A. rufus, (3) A. iraniensis sp. n. Antenna (4–6): (4) A. elegans, (5) A. rufus, (6) A. iraniensis sp. n. Sternites III–V (7–9): (7) A. elegans, (8) A. rufus, (9) A. iraniensis sp. n. Tergites VII–IX (10–12): (10) A. elegans, (11) A. rufus, (12) A. iraniensis sp. n. (13) Fore tibia and tarsus of A. iraniensis sp. n. (14) Sternites I–II of A. iraniensis sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954203/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Head convex apically; cheeks very slightly convex; eyes with pigmented facets. Antenna 6-segmented; segment I broadest, without dorsal apical setae; II globular, pedicellate; III narrower, with thin pedicel; 
<collectionCode box="[1264,1292,226,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">IV</collectionCode>
and 
<collectionCode box="[1345,1364,226,249]" country="Canada" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13946" name="Royal British Columbia Museum - Herbarium" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" type="Museum">V</collectionCode>
equal; 
<collectionCode box="[151,179,262,285]" country="Norway" name="Mykotektet, National Veterinary Institute" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">VI</collectionCode>
conical. Prothorax slender, little broader than head; ferna divided medially. Pterothorax little broader than prothorax, short. Mesonotum and metanotum each with one pair campaniform sensilla. Tarsi 1-segmented. Abdominal tergites II–VIII with no discal setae medially, but with 4–8 setae laterally, with two pairs of posterior submarginal setae (
<figureCitation box="[1356,1422,334,358]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–14" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1748,1770]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–14. Aptinothrips species.Female. Tergites III–V (1–3): (1) A. elegans, (2) A. rufus, (3) A. iraniensis sp. n. Antenna (4–6): (4) A. elegans, (5) A. rufus, (6) A. iraniensis sp. n. Sternites III–V (7–9): (7) A. elegans, (8) A. rufus, (9) A. iraniensis sp. n. Tergites VII–IX (10–12): (10) A. elegans, (11) A. rufus, (12) A. iraniensis sp. n. (13) Fore tibia and tarsus of A. iraniensis sp. n. (14) Sternites I–II of A. iraniensis sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954203/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); tergites I–VIII and X with one pair of campaniform sensilla (except 
<collectionCode box="[864,892,370,393]" country="Norway" name="Mykotektet, National Veterinary Institute" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">VI</collectionCode>
with an extra pore on right side); IX with two pairs; in a 
<typeStatus box="[202,297,406,430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">paratype</typeStatus>
, tergites II–IV each with two pairs of campaniform sensilla; tergite VIII without posteromarginal comb; setae S1 on tergite IX about half length of setae S2; tergum X with complete median longitudinal split (
<figureCitation box="[1244,1323,442,466]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–14" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1748,1770]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–14. Aptinothrips species.Female. Tergites III–V (1–3): (1) A. elegans, (2) A. rufus, (3) A. iraniensis sp. n. Antenna (4–6): (4) A. elegans, (5) A. rufus, (6) A. iraniensis sp. n. Sternites III–V (7–9): (7) A. elegans, (8) A. rufus, (9) A. iraniensis sp. n. Tergites VII–IX (10–12): (10) A. elegans, (11) A. rufus, (12) A. iraniensis sp. n. (13) Fore tibia and tarsus of A. iraniensis sp. n. (14) Sternites I–II of A. iraniensis sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954203/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
); sternite I with 2 minute anteromedian setae, II with 4 (
<quantity box="[627,667,478,502]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
one 
<typeStatus box="[717,811,478,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">paratype</typeStatus>
) (
<figureCitation box="[832,910,478,502]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–14" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1748,1770]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–14. Aptinothrips species.Female. Tergites III–V (1–3): (1) A. elegans, (2) A. rufus, (3) A. iraniensis sp. n. Antenna (4–6): (4) A. elegans, (5) A. rufus, (6) A. iraniensis sp. n. Sternites III–V (7–9): (7) A. elegans, (8) A. rufus, (9) A. iraniensis sp. n. Tergites VII–IX (10–12): (10) A. elegans, (11) A. rufus, (12) A. iraniensis sp. n. (13) Fore tibia and tarsus of A. iraniensis sp. n. (14) Sternites I–II of A. iraniensis sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954203/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
); sternite II with 2 pairs of posteromarginal setae, III–VII with 3 pairs; setae S3 longest on IV–VII, median pair on VII arising submarginally; sternite II with 2 discal setae (
<quantity box="[160,201,550,574]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
one 
<typeStatus box="[253,349,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">paratype</typeStatus>
), III–VII with 6–9 discal setae (
<figureCitation box="[688,753,550,574]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–14" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1748,1770]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,471,1720]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–14. Aptinothrips species.Female. Tergites III–V (1–3): (1) A. elegans, (2) A. rufus, (3) A. iraniensis sp. n. Antenna (4–6): (4) A. elegans, (5) A. rufus, (6) A. iraniensis sp. n. Sternites III–V (7–9): (7) A. elegans, (8) A. rufus, (9) A. iraniensis sp. n. Tergites VII–IX (10–12): (10) A. elegans, (11) A. rufus, (12) A. iraniensis sp. n. (13) Fore tibia and tarsus of A. iraniensis sp. n. (14) Sternites I–II of A. iraniensis sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954203/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); sternite VII with paired anterolateral pores
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,154,1042]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis box="[199,621,586,610]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,366,586,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Measurements</emphasis>
